<article>

  <p>
    Sitting down to meditate is not hard because the instructions are obscure. It is
    hard because the mind immediately starts negotiating — about posture, about time,
    about whether this restless stretch “counts.” Most of us have met that stall:
    the phone still warm in the hand, twenty minutes already thinning into ten, then
    into “maybe later,” then into nothing.
  </p>

  <p>
    Sitting is not the whole path. Ethics, speech, livelihood, and the rest of the
    training matter as much as any cushion. But a regular sit gives the mind a stretch
    of time in which its default moves become visible enough to work with. The canon
    has far more detail — sixteen steps of breath meditation in the
    <a href="/suttas/anapanasati/">Āṇāpānasati Sutta</a>, four foundations in the
    <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/">Satipaṭṭhāna Sutta</a>. This page is narrower:
    enough structure to begin without turning the beginning into a performance review.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Why Start with Sitting</h2>

  <p>
    Sitting still is not mystical. It is a way of reducing the usual exits —
    standing up, checking a screen, starting the next task — long enough that the
    mind’s habits can be seen. Consider an ordinary afternoon: planning slides into
    memory, memory into irritation, irritation into the itch to fix something elsewhere.
    Off the cushion, each of those moves can recruit a new action. On it, they have
    fewer places to go. They become visible as moves.
  </p>

  <p>
    The tradition calls the quality that knows what is present
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>:
    clear recollection, not losing track. Sitting does not manufacture
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    by itself. It creates conditions in which
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sati" data-en="mindfulness">sati</span>
    has a chance. The point is not to produce a blank mind or a special feeling. The
    point is to meet what is already here — breath, body, planning, dullness,
    irritation — without immediately rearranging the room.
  </p>

  <p>
    Over time that meeting supports both stillness
    (<span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="unification">samādhi</span>)
    and clear seeing. Worth holding lightly: sitting is one door. Walking, lying
    down, and ordinary daily life are also fields for the same training. Start with
    the door that is easiest to keep open.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Posture and Body</h2>

  <p>
    The body instruction is almost embarrassingly simple: upright enough to stay
    awake, relaxed enough to stay. Spine roughly vertical — not rigid military
    attention, not a soft collapse into the chair. Hands in the lap or on the thighs.
    Eyes closed, or lightly open with a soft downward gaze if closing them pulls
    toward sleep.
  </p>

  <p>
    A chair is fine. Cross-legged on a cushion is fine. Kneeling on a bench is fine.
    The tradition does not grade postures by holiness. What matters is sustainability:
    can the body remain for the planned time without injury and without constantly
    renegotiating the seat? If pain is sharp or joint-threatening, adjust. That is
    not weakness; it is not mistaking harm for discipline.
  </p>

  <p>
    Ordinary discomfort is a different case — an itch, a dull ache, the urge to
    shift again. Notice it the way one might notice a sound: present, known, not
    automatically obeyed. Comfort and collapse are not the same thing. Comfort means
    the body can settle without fighting. Collapse means alertness has left. Aim for
    the first. The body itself —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="kāya" data-en="body">kāya</span>
    in the language of the foundations of mindfulness — is already a place to rest
    attention, not only a vehicle for getting the mind somewhere else.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Duration and Rhythm</h2>

  <p>
    Short and regular beats long and heroic. Ten or fifteen minutes most days will
    teach more than an hour once, followed by a week of avoidance. The mind loves
    the drama of the heroic sit and then quietly refuses to return. Set a timer so
    attention does not have to keep checking how much is left. When the timer feels
    hostile — when every minute is a negotiation — shorten the sit rather than
    abandon the habit.
  </p>

  <p>
    Returning tomorrow matters more than winning today. A useful early rhythm is the
    same seat, roughly the same time, without requiring the same mood. Practice when
    it feels welcome and when it does not — within reason. Sleep deprivation and
    acute crisis are not the moments to force a long sit. Ordinary reluctance usually
    is. The mind that waits for ideal conditions is often waiting forever.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What to Do with the Mind</h2>

  <p>
    Choose a home base. For most beginners the breath at the nose, chest, or belly
    works well — the same territory the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="āṇāpānasati" data-en="mindfulness of breathing">āṇāpānasati</span>
    teaching develops in detail. The body as a whole — contact with the seat, the
    sense of uprightness — is another stable option. Pick one. Stay with it lightly,
    not clenched. The breath does not need to be improved. It needs to be known.
  </p>

  <p>
    The mind will leave. That is not a failure of the method; it is the method
    meeting an untrained mind. When wandering is noticed, return. No speech is
    required, but a quiet naming can help: “thinking,” “planning,” “sound.” Naming
    is not fighting. Fighting adds a second struggle on top of the first distraction —
    self-reproach piled onto ordinary mental noise. Returning without that story is
    the skill.
  </p>

  <p>
    Sometimes what pulls attention is denser than ordinary thought — desire,
    ill-will, dullness, restlessness, doubt. Those are the
    <span class="pali" data-pali="nīvaraṇa" data-en="hindrance">nīvaraṇas</span>,
    treated at length on the
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/">five hindrances</a> page. For a starting
    sit, the instruction stays the same: know what is present, return when you can.
    The hindrances do not have to be cleared before the sit counts. Seeing them is
    already part of the work.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>What “Success” Is Not</h2>

  <p>
    Success at the beginning is not a blank mind. It is not bliss. It is not a
    progress chart of deeper
    <span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">jhānas</span>
    each week. Those measures turn practice into theatre — a search for proof that
    something special is happening. A sit spent mostly lost in planning, noticed a
    few times, and returned to — that is a successful sit. The return is the
    practice. The wandering is the field.
  </p>

  <p>
    Judging a sit by how pleasant it felt trains the mind to chase pleasant sits.
    Judging it by how still the mind became trains it to treat agitation as defeat.
    A sturdier measure is quieter: Did you show up for the time you set? Did you
    know, at least sometimes, what was happening? Did you return without turning the
    return into a story about who you are?
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "Just as the ocean has a gradual shelf, a gradual slope, a gradual inclination,
    with a sudden drop-off only after a long stretch, in the same way this Dhamma
    and Discipline has a gradual training, a gradual practice, a gradual progression,
    with a penetration to gnosis only after a long stretch."
    <cite>— Ud 5.5 / AN 8.19 (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    When the timer ends, stop. Notice the body again for a moment. Carry whatever
    clarity there was — or whatever honesty about distraction there was — into the
    next ordinary task. The conditions for the next sit are mostly unglamorous:
    sleep, a clear enough schedule, and the decision not to wait for a better mood.
    Sitting is training, not theatre. Begin again tomorrow.
  </p>

</article>
